The algorithm works by checking if the last digit of the number is equal to 1 or 3, and then recursively checks the number without its last digit. This is because the last digit of a power of three can only be 1 or 3, and if `n` is a power of three, then the number without its last digit (when divided by three) must also be a power of three.

Here's the Java code:

```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) return false; // Base case: negative numbers and zero are not powers of three
    if (n % 3 == 0) { // Check if the last digit is 3
        return (n > 1) ? isPowerOfThree(n / 3) : true; // Recursively check the number without its last digit
    } else if (n % 3 == 1) { // Check if the last digit is 1
        return isPowerOfThree(n / 3); // Recursively check the number without its last digit
    } else { // The last digit is not 1 or 3
        return false;
    }
}
```

